parties which do not result in contract within the meaning of that term in
our law. The ordinary example is where two parties agree to take a walk
together, or where there is an offer and acceptance of hospitality. Nobody
would suggest in ordinary circumstances that these arrangements result in
what we know as contracts, and one of the most usual forms of agreement
which does not constitute a contract appears to be the arrangements which
are made between husband and wife. These arrangements do not result in
contracts at all, even though there may be what would constitute considera-
