Rule of construction
The results of these cases have been variable because it seems that the
theory of fundamental breach is not an independent rule of law, but is only a
rule of construction. A rule of law operates irrespective of the parties' inten-
tions. But a rule of construction is one of the methods of ascertaining the
parties' intention. This approach was "most clearly and accurately" enun-
ciated by PEARSON LJ in U.G.S. Finance Ltd v National Mortgage Bank of
Greece, S.A.238 His Lordship said:
As to the question of 'fundamental breach',... there is a rule of con-
struction that normally an exception or exclusion clause or a similar pro-
vision in a contract should be construed as not applying to a situation
created by a fundamental breach of contract. This is not an independent
rule of law imposed by the courts on the parties willy-nilly in disregard
to their contractual intention. On the contrary, it is a rule of construction
based on the presumed intention of the contracting parties. It involves
the implication of a term to give to the contract that business efficacy
which the parties reasonably must have intended it to have. This rule of
construction is not new in principle but it has become prominent in recent
years in consequence of the tendency to have standard forms of contract
containing exception clauses drawn in extravagantly wide terms, which
would have produced absurd results if applied literally.
