7. Exemption clauses and third parties
One of the basic principles of the law of contract is that a contract is a
contract only between the parties to it and no third party can either enjoy
any rights or suffer any liability under it.291 This should apply to standard
form contracts also. The effect would be that where goods are supplied or
services rendered under a contract which exempts the supplier from liability
