Past act at request good consideration
However, an important exception is almost as old as the rule itself. It was
established as early as 1616 in Lampleigh v Brathwait that a past act done
at request will be good consideration for a subsequent promise. The facts
were:
The defendant, having committed a murder, requested the plaintiff to
labour and to do his endeavour to obtain pardon from the King. The
plaintiff did his best to obtain the King's pardon, riding and journeying at
his own expense. Afterwards the defendant promised the plaintiff to give
him £100 and then refused to pay. He was, however, held liable.
