When silence is fraud
But then how far may silence go? Silence may become deceptive in certain
cases.
1. Duty to speak (contracts uberrima fides)
The first such case is when the person keeping silence is under duty to
speak. Duty to speak arises where one contracting party reposes trust and
confidence in the other. A father, for example, selling a horse to his son must
tell him if the horse is unsound, as the son is likely to rely upon his father.
