case the mistake related to a minor distance. The fact would have become
more important and essential to the contract if a longer distance had been
involved. Speaking broadly, certain facts are essential to every agreement.
They are:
(1) The identity of the parties;
(2) the identity and nature of the subject-matter of the contract; and
(3) the nature and content of the promise itself.
