contract.
Effect of such failure when time is not essential.-If it was not the inten-
tion of the parties that time should be of the essence of the contract, the con-
tract does not become voidable by the failure to do such thing at or before the
specified time; but the promisee is entitled to compensation from the promisor
for any loss occasioned to him by such failure.
