When the parties to a contract agree to substitute the existing contract
with a new contract, that is called novation. 321 In the well-known case of
Scarf v Jardine³2 Lord SELBORNE explained the meaning and effect of nova-
tion in the following words:
... there being a contract in existence, some new contract is substituted
for it either between the same parties or between different parties, the
