There are many situations in which law as well as justice require that a
certain person be required to conform to an obligation, although he has
neither broken any contract nor committed any tort. For example, a person
in whose home certain goods have been left by mistake is bound to restore
them. Such obligations are generally described, for want of a better or more
appropriate name, as quasi-contractual obligations.
Rationale
Theory of unjust enrichment
